Question:
Collect all even numbers into a new list and print.
Input:
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6);

Solution:
Java 8 Streams collect even numbers using filter(n -> n % 2 == 0) then collect(Collectors.toList()). For input [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6], creates new list [2, 4, 6] and prints it.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream the list via stream(). Filter even numbers with filter(num -> num % 2 == 0). Collect to new List<Integer> using Collectors.toList(). Print the resulting list.

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class CollectEvenNumbers {
    public static void collectAndPrintEven(List<Integer> numbers) {
        List<Integer> evens = numbers.stream()
                                     .filter(num -> num % 2 == 0)
                                     .collect(Collectors.toList());
        System.out.println(evens);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6);
        collectAndPrintEven(list);
    }
}

Prints [2, 4, 6]. Original list unchanged; new list created.

#Thought Process
filter intermediate op reduces stream to evens (predicate returns boolean). collect(toList()) terminal gathers into ArrayList. % 2 == 0 standard even check. Sequential preserves order.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Returns empty list [].
Null list: NPE on stream(); precondition null-check.
Null elements: null % 2 → NPE; filter Objects::nonNull first.
No evens: Returns [].
All evens: Returns copy of input.
Zero: 0 % 2 == 0 true (even).
Negatives: -2 % 2 == 0 true (even in Java).
Single element: [1] → []; [2] → [2].
Large lists: O(n) filter + O(k) collect; parallelStream preserves order for filter.
